<h1>
<seg id="1">Poland and the cosmos.</seg>
</h1>
<p>
<seg id="2">Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on November 12, 2008).</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="3">Poland had begun a close collaboration with ESA in 1994, and over the ensuing years has participated in a number of projects for the agency.</seg>
<seg id="4">The road from Poland to space, however, began much earlier.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5">Already before the Second World War, Poles who worked on space flights; they do not always meet understanding.</seg>
<seg id="6">For example, I would like to mention the conference of A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his pioneering book entitled "Introduction to cosmonautics."</seg>
<seg id="7">The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left audiences cold and years later Šternfeld recalled that only the doctor Jan Gadomski became interested in its work.</seg>
<seg id="8">In 1934, Šternfeld in France won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for his book "Introduction to cosmonautics."</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="9">The doctor Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.</seg>
<seg id="10">He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.</seg>
<seg id="11">Gadomski became a propagator of astronautics of world renown, his contribution has been rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="12">As early as 1925 was built in Poland railway intended to be equipped with a rocket engine.</seg>
<seg id="13">Unfortunately, there is neither the author nor the details of this project.</seg>
<seg id="14">It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or slow the speeder.</seg>
<seg id="15">The only information known about this speeder are those of the press at the time.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="16">In 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote himself to rockets.</seg>
<seg id="17">The research was conducted by the institute Komórka en Automobielbedrijf tromp Uzbrojenia in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.</seg>
<seg id="18">It is clear from the documents that this research had reached the stage of testing.</seg>
<seg id="19">Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research stalled.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="20">In 1937, plans a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the press, and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - Torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.</seg>
<seg id="21">These two projects were directed military use of rocket engines.</seg>
<seg id="22">Just before the war, all plans for the use of the technique of rockets were carried out by the Scientific Advisory Committee ("provisional TYMCZASOWY Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), who coordinated all work.</seg>
<seg id="23">This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war put an end to its activities.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="24">After the war, other work on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).</seg>
<seg id="25">For the first time, it is a question of a company in the November issue of the journal Problem, 1954, in which four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.</seg>
<seg id="26">In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company devoted to astronautics</seg>
<seg id="27">At that time, projects of artificial satellites had already been launched, and it was clear that the field of space research in the future.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="28">At the beginning of the year 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) deployed efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.</seg>
<seg id="29">The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.</seg>
<seg id="30">He retained his position until his death in 1959.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="31">Since 1956, the PTA brought a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.</seg>
<seg id="32">The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.</seg>
<seg id="33">This rocket with a range of 1800 metres had a length of 80 cm and weighed just under 5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="34">Subsequently was built an improved version, RM-1A, and during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage rocket RM-2 were started in the desert of Bledov.</seg>
<seg id="35">This rocket had a length of 1.4m and weighed probably 11.5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="36">Following the prototype should be able to make concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind aloft.</seg>
<seg id="37">But in 1963, all development work was stopped.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="38">The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.</seg>
<seg id="39">This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.</seg>
<seg id="40">Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the size of the space reserved for scientific tools.</seg>
<seg id="41">The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litre, whereas in Meteor-1B this volume was $0.34 per litre and Meteor-1C 0.62 litre.</seg>
<seg id="42">The maximum range of all these types of gear was 37 km.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="43">In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aviation institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.</seg>
<seg id="44">The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.</seg>
<seg id="45">Later versions were built Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="46">It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland to the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960, and the creation of a national committee COSPAR two years later.</seg>
<seg id="47">Under the programme Interkosmos, Poland has also participated in space exploration on the Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut.</seg>
</p>
