<h1>
<seg id="1">The repeal of the law on the public work is not a solution.</seg>
</h1>
<p>
<seg id="2">Last week, the Constitutional Court has repealed the law on public work.</seg>
<seg id="3">This decision has raised public opinion in a heated discussion.</seg>
<seg id="4">It is certainly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="5">The economic systems geared towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">This means that the various economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.</seg>
<seg id="7">This is the result of the principle of freedom of trade and the free movement (without limits) of private capital, combined with an unbridled financial speculation.</seg>
<seg id="8">The considerable differences in the price of labour (wages) generate pressure on prices.</seg>
<seg id="9">It should be put under this term the following meaning: A producer tries by the importation of goods sold cheaply to resist economic competition by making it more expensive, "" the price of a competitor, in order to remove a larger share of the market and thereby increase its own profits.</seg>
<seg id="10">On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: Either transferring production abroad, or buy cheap or disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour costs are high in comparison to other economies.</seg>
<seg id="11">Given that the private capital has no responsibility for the social point of view and thereby responsibility vis-à-vis the unemployment that it generates, the social costs of the State necessarily increase.</seg>
<seg id="12">This whole situation intensifies the perfect gentlemen entrepreneurs's unwillingness to pay taxes and to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.</seg>
<seg id="13">This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistics.</seg>
<seg id="14">The unscrupulous practices of private capital in different economies create a situation in which the governments of various countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own people in order to attract foreign capital.</seg>
<seg id="15">In other words, governments are putting their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking account of the social collapse.</seg>
<seg id="16">This occurs mainly in the amendments of the laws in force.</seg>
<seg id="17">The goal is to compel economically its own people to accept the dictates of the price of private capital, particularly in the area of wages.</seg>
<seg id="18">This occurs by a system of economic constraints in the case of long-term unemployment and by restricting the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.</seg>
<seg id="19">The result is a growing poverty and the deepening of the differences between the rich and poor.</seg>
<seg id="20">In Germany, there are for years points of public distribution of food for the poor who cannot meet their needs with their own work.</seg>
<seg id="21">There are already a million the number of these people.</seg>
<seg id="22">In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for employees receive such salaries that the state was forced to pay a premium to reach the subsistence level.</seg>
<seg id="23">Such a scandal, for example, has been updated in the case of employees working as auxiliaries to the federal parliament.</seg>
<seg id="24">The economy measures of virtually all the southern Member States of the EU are, without doubt, a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) or to eke out a living with poverty wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day the private capital to invest in their country.</seg>
<seg id="25">Here we need to ask the question: Where will this capital?</seg>
<seg id="26">If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will increase from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.</seg>
<seg id="27">This also applies to all of Latin America.</seg>
<seg id="28">The liberal theory and the media claim to have enough of it, that the State cannot make capital investments in its own economy, the command economy led to an economic disaster.</seg>
<seg id="29">Private capital is very much in the idea that the state may not intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.</seg>
<seg id="30">We must then ask whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not run today, according to its own selfish interests, and by the same policy, the entire state.</seg>
<seg id="31">The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.</seg>
<seg id="32">The proof is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby and present in all states.</seg>
<seg id="33">The result is a desperate situation occurring in the field of corruption, by the granting of mutual benefits in the legislation, where everything is wrong but not punishable.</seg>
<seg id="34">In Germany, the situation is such that, because of the lack of financial resources, the national ministries delegate the preparation of draft laws to law firms closely tied to the industry.</seg>
<seg id="35">These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.</seg>
<seg id="36">All the power comes not from the people, as the Western-style constitutions, but powerful financial groups serving their own interests.</seg>
<seg id="37">It is clear that democracies are oriented towards liberalism now quickly face the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "the crisis of the Roman Empire at the time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State has long been deteriorating and functions were assigned by violence.</seg>
<seg id="38">The blows of bribes, favors received illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.</seg>
<seg id="39">The kickbacks and corruption were spreading without limits and the people went to the election with votes already sold... "..." The honest people do not seek to obtain functions, the result was once the State went 8 months without consuls... "'It began really to say that the cure for this difficult situation was an autocracy and that he had to choose an energetic man..." It is true that Pompey Appianos had in mind, but it is Caesar who transformed irreversibly democracy in the absolutist regime.</seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id="40">In conclusion, as in antiquity, today's society is based on the preference of the personal benefit, without regard for the interests of society as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="41">In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and to advance the interests of society as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="42">As a result, today as in the past, an unprecedented decadence of elites, without any effort to conduct in-depth reforms.</seg>
<seg id="43">We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in unscrupulous liberalization of economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.</seg>
<seg id="44">In the current state of affairs, we can consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies such as a sort of pause before a new stage.</seg>
<seg id="45">The fact that the current elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the social and humanitarian crises that we are now witnessing as well as crimes against humanity as we know them by recent and ancient history.</seg>
<seg id="46">The repeal of the law on public work is not a solution, at least in the long term.</seg>
<seg id="47">Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and domestically, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.</seg>
<seg id="48">This trend is indeed systemic.</seg>
<seg id="49">The solution is subject to socio-political reforms, which will strengthen the capital investment of the state in the economy, will increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the State.</seg>
</p>
